barobaTN 
[The Persian lute;] a certain musical instrument (Lth, Mṣb) of the Eajama [or Persians]; (Mṣb;) i. q. EuwidN: (Lth, Ḳ:) an arabicized word, (Ḳ,) from baribato, (IAth,) or baribaTo; meaning “the breast of the duck, or goose;” because of its resemblance thereto; (Ḳ;) 


for baro in Persian, signifies the “breast;” (TA;) [and bato and baTo or baT-o, like the Arabic baT-N, “a duck,” or “goose;”] or because the player upon it places it against his breast: (IAth:) or it is said to be arabicized because it is the name of a musical instrument of the Ejm. (Mṣb.)

