entry.sense:
baAzilN, applied to a camel, the male and the female, (Ṣ, Mgh, Mṣb, Ḳ,) That has cut its nAb [or tush]; (Ṣ, Mṣb, Ḳ;) by its entering the ninth year; (Mṣb;) or in its ninth year; (Ṣ, Mgh, Ḳ;) for then it cuts that tooth; (Ṣ, Ḳ;) or, as is sometimes the case, in the eighth year; (Ṣ;) and after this there is no age named: (IAạr, Ḳ:) or a she-camel that has completed her ninth year, and attained her full strength: (Ḥam p. 506:) 
and bazuwlN↓ signifies the same, applied to the male and the female: (IDrd, Ḳ:) or, accord. to AZ, a she-camel is not termed baAzilN; 
but the epithet bazuwlN↓ is applied to her that has completed a year after cutting the tooth above mentioned, until she is termed nAb: (MF, TA:) the pl. (of bAzl, Ṣ, Mṣb) is bawaAzilu (Ṣ, Mṣb, Ḳ) and buz-alN (Ṣ, Ḳ) and buzolN, (Ṣ,) or buzulN, like kutubN. (Ḳ.) baAzilu EaAmK and baAzilu EaAmayoni signify That has passed a year, and two years, after cutting the tooth above mentioned. (MF, TA.)

bisil-aI 
[more commonly written in the present day bisil-ap] A certain kind of grain like the lupine (turomus), or less than this; 
[the pea termed by Linnæus pisum arvense:] a word of the dial. of Egypt. (TA.)

Applied to milk, and to nabiyc [or must, &c.] ‡ Strong: (Ḳ:) or, applied to the former, displeasing, or odious, in taste, and sour; and applied to the latter, strong and sour. (M, TA.) 
And, applied to vinegar, † Altered, or corrupted, in flavour, from having been left long; 
as also mubas-alN↓ (Az in art. Hcq, TA.)

