baTanN 
Disease of the belly, (Ḳ, TA,) being a state of enlargement thereof arising from satiety; 
and so baTonN↓; whence the phrase maAta biAlbaToni He died by the disease of the belly. (TA.)

baTiynN, applied to a man, (Ḳ,) Big, or large, in the belly; (Ṣ, Ḳ;) 
as also miboTaAnN↓: the former occurs, in a description of ʼAlee, used as an epithet of praise: and signifies also big, or large, in the belly in consequence of much eating: and having the belly full; 
as also ↓the latter: pl. of the former biTaAnN. (TA.)

AlbuTayonu 
One of the Mansions of the Moon; (Ṣ, Ḳ;) namely, the Second; (Ḳzw, &c.;) three small stars 
[e and p and n], (Ṣ, Ḳ,) disposed in the form of an equilateral triangle, (Ṣ,) as though they were three stones whereon a cooking-pot is placed, and forming the belly of the Ram; (Ṣ, Ḳ;) the appellation being made a diminutive because the Ram consists of many stars in the form of a ram; 
[so I here render Hamal though it properly signifies a lamb;] the XazaTaAni being its two horns; and the buTayon, its belly; 
[or, accord. to our configuration of Aries, the rump;] and the vuray-aA, its rump, or tail; (Ṣ;) three obscure stars, forming the points of a triangle, in the belly of the Ram, between the XaraTaAni and the vuray-aA; (Ḳzw, Mir-át ez-Zemán, &c.;) the three stars of which two are on the tail and one on the thigh of the Ram, forming an equilateral triangle. (Ḳzw in his description of Aries.) 
[See manaAzilu Alqamari, 
in art. nzl.] 
The Arabs assert that it has no nawoC 
[here meaning effect upon the weather], 
except wind. (TA.)

baEovN an inf. n. used as a pass. part. n.; Sent; 
as also baEiyvN↓ 
and maboEwvN↓: pl. of the first buEuwvN; and of the second buEuvN. (L, TA.)

